"I wish more people would celebrate this new discovery rather than bring up every little unrelated nugget they've been carrying around hoping someday they could have their 5" of attention."Although DES was pulled off the market decades ago, it's still an issue as far as fertility is concerned, because there are several million people alive today who were exposed to it in the womb, some of whom are still of childbearing age (particularly in Europe, where DES usage peaked a lot later than it did in America). Also, there's some evidence to suggest that the fertility problems can persist into the third generation (DES grandchildren), and of course there's also the fact that, every day, millions of women around the world are taking contraceptive hormones with similar endocrine disrupting properties to DES!



